Initial Setup for RSTPY Lab¶

Objective:¶

Setup the initial Lab environmnet.

  • Install Visual Studio Code on the Windows Jumphost

    • Download Visual Studio Code:

      Open Chrome browser and in the search bar, type vscode download

      The first search link should take you to the following site:

      VSCode Download Page https://code.visualstudio.com/download

      Click on the Windows logo to download the installer:

      Once downloaded, Click to access the downloads folder:

    • Run the VSCode Setup Installer:

    • Do the VS Code Onboarding:

      Select the Theme to your preference

      When done, click on Mark Done

    • Install the following VS Code Extension on Windows:

      • Remote SSH

      In the left hand Activity Bar, click on the Extensions icon:

      In the Extensions Search for Remote SSH Extension by Microsoft. We will need it to connect to the Linux machine centos1

      Click on the Install Button as shown above.

      Once the extension is installed, the Remote Explorer icon should become available in the Activity Bar

      Click on the Remote Explorer, then Click on the + to add a connection to the Linux host

      In the Enter SSH Connection Command dialog box, enter root@centos1 to connect to the Linux server where Python and git are installed. We will use that machine's environment to do our programming. VS Code will install a mini server on the Linux machine so that we can have a VS Code window running on the Windows Jumphost that connects to the Linux centos1.

      In the Select SSH configuration file to update dialog, select the config file in the .ssh folder in the user's home directory as shown below:

      At the bottom right of the VS Code window, you should see a pop-up, Click on Connect

      In the Select the platform of the remote host "centosl" dialog, select Linux.

      Confirm the fingerprint of the centos1 host by clicking on Continue:

      In the Enter password for root@centosl dialog box, enter the password for the root user Netapp1!

      At the bottom of the VS Code window, note that you are now connected to centos1

    • Set up Public Key Authentication

      In the centos1 connected VS Code window, Press CTRL+` to open a terminal on the linux host. Note that it is the back tick character and not a single qoute character. Alternatively, you can click on Terminal from the View Menu.

      In the terminal, type ssh-keygen to generate a public/private key pair for the root user on the linux machine. This will also create the required .ssh directory with the correct permissions. We will copy the Windows administrator's public key to the authorized_keys file in this .ssh folder to allow for passwordless, public key authentication from the Windows machine.

      For the location of the key file, accept th default location and use an empty passphrase as shown below:

      On the Windows Jumphost, open a powershell window, and type ssh-keygen as we did in the Linux terminal through VS Code. Again accept the default location for the key files and and empty passphrase.

      We will then copy the public key to the authorized_keys file on the linux host. To do this, cd to the .ssh folder on the Jumphost powershell window and run the following command:

      scp .\id_rsa.pub root@centos1:~/.ssh/authorized_keys

      Accept the fingerprint displayed.

      Going back the the VS Code window connected to the centos1, in the terminal, edit the /etc/ssh/sshd_config file to allow Public Key authentication.

      • Edit /etc/ssh/sshd_config on centos1 to allow PubkeyAuthentication

        • vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config

        • in vi, Enter the keystrokes exactly: /Pubkey ENTER yy p x :wq ENTER

          • Explanation of the keystrokes:

            Search for Pubkey by typing: /Pubkey followed by ENTER key

            Yank the line : yy

            Paste the line: p

            Delete the comment # character at the beginning of the line by pressing: x

            Save and exit vi :wq Enter

      • Restart sshd

        systemctl restart sshd.service

    • You can move the terminal to a full pane by doing the following:

      Click on the Terminal, then select Move Terminal to Editor Area
